data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire `Expression.Lambda` / `Expression.Call` construction **won't compile**. Replace it with a simple lambda:

```csharp
// .NET 10
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No manual expression tree building needed — conditionals work directly inside the lambda body now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes generate schema-breaking migrations

**a) Duplicate property names across complex types** are now auto-uniquified (e.g. `Street` → `Street1`).  
**b) Nested complex types** now include the full path (`Complex_NestedComplex_Property` instead of `NestedComplex_Property`).

Pin the old column names with `HasColumnName()` to avoid a data-breaking migration:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, ab =>
    {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street");
    });
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ab =>
    {
        ab.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street");
    });
});

// For nested: Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, pb =>
    {
        pb.ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress, ab =>
        {
            // Was "BillingAddress_City", now defaults to "Payment_BillingAddress_City"
            ab.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
        });
    });
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (redacted SQL for safe logging). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual SQL
    }
}
```

Apply the same addition to any other methods you implement (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.).
